author: @Alexander-h5s1d
comment:
I use GNU/Linux everyday, and have for months, but I can say that Windows and macOS aren‚Äôt bad operating systems; in fact, they‚Äôre really good, but the only reason I don‚Äôt use either is because of privacy and well‚Ä¶ my computer is an old fella, and trying to run Windows 11 on 4 GiB of DDR3 is impossible. It runs way too slow, so, I use GNU/Linux. Windows is great for software, but because of Wine on GNU/Linux I can run all .exe files on my computer. As for macOS? Yeah, no, I‚Äôm not using macOS applications. I will say that it‚Äôs worth it to try out daily driving Debian or Fedora (GNU/Linux distribution) for a month. You‚Äôll either love it, or hate it, but either way you‚Äôll enjoy it to some degree. Have fun, bro, and enjoy your programming deviousness!

Edit: My reasoning for picking Debian and Fedora is because they‚Äôre both really good. Some will say to use Ubuntu, but Ubuntu is just a branch of Debian. Debian runs a TON of stuff. As for Fedora, it‚Äôs just so you get taste of something else. However, whatever you do, do NOT pick Arch as your first distribution, you‚Äôll give up quickly unless you use archinstall.

author: @Frobbing
comment: 18:53 There's actually a faster way. You need to do these inputs in order while holding shift: Hotkey -> left click -> hotkey -> left click, where hotkey means a hotbar hotkey like 1, 2, 3, etc. or swap with off-hand button. This will move all items of the same type into your inventory, like in the third example, but without leaving a stack on your cursor or even having to move the mouse. Probably no real improvement, but interesting nontheless.

author: @AnnieBot4573
comment:
1:13 subscribed for that sense of humor, GD
another solution for the mouse trick is to keybind the left-click to the number pad, hold down the key, and then turn number lock off. the computer doesn't receive the signal that the key is no longer being pressed. also works for power semi-automation in diablo 3
windows is for normies, linux is for coders (and wannabe coders who hate themselves), and mac is for retards who have too much money
5:40 the redstone for the chicken cooker is too complicated. much easier to do tripwire in a chute with a line of redstone coming off each side with repeaters. set one side to 1 tick delay and the other to 5 ticks delay. this will cook  and kill the chicken, but take the lava away before burning the loot, and because it only activates when something triggers the tripwire, servers won't flag it as a lag machine
